    "summary": "Abstract Flooded forests surrounding Tonlé Sap Lake represent one of the most ecologically important wetland forest systems in Southeast Asia. These forests play a crucial role in maintaining biodiversity, regulating hydrological processes, and supporting fisheries productivity in the Mekong Basin. The structure and species composition of flooded forests are shaped primarily by seasonal flooding regimes, soil conditions, and human disturbances. This review synthesizes existing literature on the structural characteristics, dominant species, and ecological dynamics of flooded forests in the Tonlé Sap floodplain. The findings indicate that these forests are dominated by flood-tolerant tree species with relatively low canopy height but high ecological productivity. However, increasing pressure"
